'9:1': [
{sup:"1a", word:"weep", vrefs:"Isa. 22:4; Jer. 4:19; 13:17; Lam. 2:11; 3:48", lines:["Jehovah came in to correct His hypocritical worshippers, and Jeremiah reacted to Jehovah&rsquo;s correction of Israel ({Jer8:18|8:18}-{Jer8:19|19}, {Jer8:21|21}-{Jer8:22|22}; {Jer9:1|9:1}-{Jer9:2|2}; {Jer10:19|10:19}-{Jer10:25|25}). The prophet&rsquo;s reaction was very tender, sympathetic, and compassionate.","According to this book, God&rsquo;s love is a composition of His tender care, compassion, and sympathy. Even while He chastises His elect people Israel, He is compassionate toward them ({Lam3:22|Lam. 3:22}-{Lam3:23|23}). In His chastising of Israel, God can be compared to a father who weeps as he disciplines his child because he loves the child. In this book Jeremiah wept on God&rsquo;s behalf; his weeping expressed God&rsquo;s feeling. We may say that God wept within Jeremiah&rsquo;s weeping, for in his weeping Jeremiah was one with God. Because Jeremiah often wept ({Jer13:17|13:17}; {Lam2:11|Lam. 2:11}; {Lam3:48|3:48}), even wailed, he is called the weeping prophet."]},
],
